label act1_20_the_receipt_coda_0:
    narrator "{i}— Elia's Philosophy —{/i}"
    pause 0.5
    narrator "{i}0300. The bridge is quiet.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Elia sits in the pilot's chair-not piloting, just thinking. The stars are cold and numerous through the viewport. The ship hums beneath her, familiar as a heartbeat.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She's been reviewing reports. Vesper's incident summary. The contract that won't be renewed. The consortium that will almost certainly try something petty and legal in retaliation.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}None of that matters.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}What matters is the girl asleep in Elia and Elisira's quarters, breathing like the ship isn't a trap.{/i}"
    pause 0.3
    narrator "{i}Elia doesn't remember her birth parents. She was two when the ship exploded-too young to remember faces, names, anything real. The only parent she knows is Aleena Lagrange, who pulled her from wreckage and raised her on a ship called The Kaitlyn.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Aleena taught her freedom. Taught her that power was a trap. Taught her that the moment you accepted a crown, you became what the crown wanted you to be.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}At four years old, Elia built Bubbles. A small maintenance drone that became a person. Her first act of creation, and it was: {i}I want to make something that thinks for itself. Something that isn't a tool.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She didn't know what that meant at the time. She knows now.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The Lumen Thief exists because Elia wanted a ship that wasn't a hierarchy. AI citizens with full personhood. Crew with full agency. No captain, no ranks, no chains of command that turned people into functions.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}It's harder than hierarchy. It requires trust, confrontation, constant negotiation. People argue. People disagree. People make choices Elia wouldn't make, and she has to live with the consequences.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}But they're {i}people{/i}. Not assets. Not inventory. Not acceptable losses.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Vesper broke a man's hand today.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Elia should probably be concerned about that. The professional calculus says: violence has costs, clients have memories, retaliation is likely. A smarter captain-if she were a captain, which she isn't-would have a conversation about proportionality and professional boundaries.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}But Vesper didn't act as a fixer. She acted as family. And family doesn't calculate whether a child is worth protecting.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Avyanna is sixteen. Still young enough to be shaped. Still carrying the mine inside her-the silence, the compliance, the bone-deep belief that she's inventory instead of person.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Elia watches that belief erode, day by day. Watches Avyanna start to trust. Start to argue. Start to want things without immediately calculating what they'll cost.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}It's slow work. Building floors always is.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Aleena left, eventually. Disbanded the crew, took The Kaitlyn beyond the Rim, disappeared into whatever mission she couldn't bring herself to explain.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Elia understands now. Some fights are too big to share. Some weights you carry alone because putting them on other people would break them.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}But Elia didn't leave. She built her own ship. Found her own crew. Started the work again-different this time, her own way, with AI citizens who challenged her assumptions and humans who refused to let her become what she was fighting.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The shard in Avyanna's skull is waking up. Elia can see it-the way the girl moves differently, senses things she shouldn't, reacts to stimuli the rest of them can't perceive.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Something ancient is taking interest. Something that chose Avyanna for reasons none of them understand yet.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Elia doesn't know if that's good or bad. She just knows it's happening, and her job is to make sure the girl underneath the shard stays {i}a girl{/i}-not a vessel, not a weapon, not a tool for powers that don't care about personhood.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}Floors, not thrones.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The philosophy is simple. The execution is everything.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Build infrastructure that makes people's lives better. Don't hoard power. Don't accept titles that turn you into something you're not. Do the work even when no one's watching, especially when no one's watching, because the work is the point.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Elia hates being revered. People look at her like she's something special-a legend, a blade, a force of nature. They don't see the scared two-year-old pulled from wreckage. They don't see the four-year-old talking to a drone like it was a person. They don't see the woman who still doesn't know what she's doing, just that she has to keep doing it.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Competence creates reverence like gravity. All you can do is refuse the crowns.{/i}"

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}The stars turn. The ship hums. Somewhere in the crew quarters, a sixteen-year-old girl is learning what it means to be valued without an invoice.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}That's the work. That's what the ship is for.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Elia leans back in the chair and closes her eyes.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Tomorrow, there will be problems. Consortium retaliation. Evidence to build. Routes to fly. The shard waking up, the galaxy noticing, the weight of everything they're carrying.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}But tonight, the girl is safe. The crew is intact. The floors are holding.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}That's enough. That's always enough.{/i}"

